definition.value: This cell type is compatible with the HIPC Lyoplate markers for 'Treg'.  The inclusion of CD127lo in the logical definition is compatible with both human and mouse T cells of this subtype.

Note that while T cells of this subset are loosely referred to 'cytotoxic T cells,' as many other T cell types, including CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells and gamma-delta T cells exhibit cytotoxicity in vitro and in vivo.
Note that gamma-delta T cells have both thymic and extrathymic differentiation pathways.

CD4-negative CD8-negative gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell

definition.value: Note that this type of thymocyte has passed the beta-selection checkpoint and is rapidly proliferating and rearranging the T cell receptor alpha chain and expressing the CD8 coreceptor. This stage comes between the DN4 and DP stages.

Note that this type of thymocyte is at the earliest stage of T cell receptor rearrangement of the beta, gamma, and delta T cell receptor chains. Also, there is growing evidence that molecular markers characterizing double negative thymocytes are different across species, especially in mouse versus human thymus. If in doubt, please consider using CL:0002489 'double negative thymocyte'.

Note that this type of thymocyte has passed the beta-selection checkpoint and is rapidly proliferating and beginning to rearrange the T cell receptor alpha chain. Thymocytes of this stage are undergoing positive and negative selection.

There are small numbers of B-1 cells found in the lymph nodes and spleen, while larger numbers can be found in the peritoneal and pleural cavities. In mouse the NKR are Ly49 molecules and in human these cells express KIR molecules.

These cells also express the transcription factors GATA-1, GATA-2, and MITF, but not C/EBPa.
